<div class="grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-12 lg:items-start">
  <div class="lg:col-span-8">
    <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold tracking-tight sm:text-4xl">Privacy</h1>
    <p class="mt-3 text-base leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
      Privacy is about reducing unnecessary exposure while keeping life usable. This page focuses on identity protection,
      account recovery, and practical “real life” situations (students, families, and community groups).
    </p>

    <section id="identity" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Identity protection (high impact)</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
          <h3 class="font-bold">Freeze your credit</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            A credit freeze helps stop new-account fraud. You can temporarily lift it when you actually need new credit.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
          <h3 class="font-bold">Protect your “core” accounts</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            Email + Apple/Google + your phone number are the recovery keys. Secure these first (unique password + MFA).
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
          <h3 class="font-bold">Watch for SIM-swap</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            Attackers can move your number to a new SIM to intercept SMS. Ask your carrier for a port-out PIN.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
          <h3 class="font-bold">Use official reporting flows</h3>
          <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
            For identity theft, start at
            <a
              class="underline underline-offset-4"
              href="https://www.identitytheft.gov/"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noreferrer"
              >IdentityTheft.gov</a
            >
            (FTC).
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="identity-response" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">If identity theft happens</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          If you discover fraudulent accounts, a scam payment, or suspicious activity tied to your identity, use the
          official FTC flows to create a recovery plan and documentation you can share with institutions.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          <li>
            <a
              class="font-semibold underline underline-offset-4"
              href="https://www.identitytheft.gov/"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noreferrer"
              >IdentityTheft.gov</a
            >
            — step-by-step recovery plan and letters
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              class="font-semibold underline underline-offset-4"
              href="https://reportfraud.ftc.gov/"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noreferrer"
              >ReportFraud.ftc.gov</a
            >
            — report scams and fraud to the FTC
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          If there’s a cybercrime component (account takeover, wire fraud, marketplace fraud), see
          <a class="font-semibold underline underline-offset-4" href="/local-resources#cybercrime"
            >Resources → Cybercrime reporting</a
          >.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="data-brokers" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Data brokers (people-search sites)</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
        <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          Many “people search” sites aggregate addresses, relatives, and phone numbers. You can reduce exposure by opting
          out, but it takes time and repetition.
        </p>
        <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          <li><strong>Search yourself</strong> using your name + city/state to find where you appear.</li>
          <li><strong>Opt out</strong> using each site’s official opt-out form.</li>
          <li><strong>Re-check monthly</strong> for a while; listings reappear.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="utah-privacy" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Utah privacy resources</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          <li>
            <a class="font-semibold underline underline-offset-4" href="https://privacy.utah.gov/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer"
              >Utah Office of Data Privacy</a
            >
            — privacy resources and guidance
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              class="font-semibold underline underline-offset-4"
              href="https://privacy.utah.gov/tools-and-resources/"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noreferrer"
              >Utah Office of Data Privacy: Tools & Resources</a
            >
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              class="font-semibold underline underline-offset-4"
              href="https://www.utah.gov/support/security.html"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noreferrer"
              >Utah.gov Security</a
            >
            — state portal for security guidance and support links
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="social" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">Social sharing rules of thumb</h2>
      <ul class="mt-4 space-y-2 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
        <li><strong>Make default privacy stricter</strong> (friends-only, limited audience).</li>
        <li><strong>Hide your friends list</strong> where possible (it’s a map of relationships).</li>
        <li><strong>Avoid posting routines</strong> (work shifts, weekly classes, kid pickup times).</li>
        <li><strong>Don’t post documents</strong>: tickets, badges, mail, screenshots with addresses.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="students" class="mt-10 scroll-mt-24">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold">For students (and anyone on campus)</h2>
      <div class="mt-4 rounded-2xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-6 dark:border-slate-800 dark:bg-slate-900">
        <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
          <li><strong>Lock down your school email</strong>: MFA + recovery options.</li>
          <li>
            <strong>Be cautious with public profiles</strong> that include class schedule or dorm location hints.
          </li>
          <li><strong>Report threats early</strong> using official campus and local channels.</li>
          <li><strong>Don’t “investigate” stalkerware alone</strong>; preserve evidence and get help.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>
